= Infinite-Dimensional Vector Spaces

We briefly discuss polynomials over a single variable, some subsets of which form infinite-dimensional vector spaces.

Let $P(FF)$ be the set of polynomials in the variable $x$ with coefficients in $FF$. That is,

$
  P(FF) := { a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2 + dots.c + a_n x^n : a_i in FF thick forall i in [n] }.
$

The degree of a nonzero polynomial $f(x) = a_0 + a_1 x + dots.c + a_n x^n$, denoted by $deg(f)$, is the largest nonnegative integer $n$ for which $a_n != 0$. For example,

$
  f(x) = 2x + x^4 => deg(f) = 4.
$

It is convenient to define $deg(bold(0))$ to be $-oo$. Note that the degree of any constant polynomial is zero.

Now, define $P_m (FF)$ to be polynomials in $x$ with degrees at most $m$.

$
  P_m (FF) := { f in P(FF) : deg(f) <= m }.
$

#exercise(number: none)[
